 That is not to say, however, that Watts chemical interests were not philosophical
 Even as the Delftfield Pottery was founded, the popularity of Delftware was beginning to wane
 There were two possible paths that Watt could pursue: to make Chinese porcelain or improve Britains existing domestic pottery
 Learning the secrets of this manufac - turing process was a project played out across Europe: it was first mastered in Dresden in 1709 under conditions of tremendous secrecy, and became a preserve of royal factories making luxurious tablewares for monarchs and their courts
 The alternative to a new domestic porcelain industry was to develop the already extant British earthenware trade
 Watts experiments on the bodies of his pottery wares were diverse
 While travelling to Birmingham in 1774, Watt also conscientiously noted that the ‘stone grows softer and gravel harder; he certainly developed a canny eye for potentially useful materials to employ at (1)(2)
 The success of Watts chemical work is suggested by the Scottish potter Robert Muirhead, who described one of his recipes for a fine, white glaze as ‘an entirely new art >>>>>> not discovered & practised by any other persons in Britain
